## What I Did

I deployed a simple HTML app with an nginx server. I also containerized the app and made a GitHub workflow for automatic deployment.

I used nginx because I need a server to serve my file. Without it, the HTML file would only be accessible on my local machine and would not be available when my laptop shuts down.

I dockerized it so the file can run on any machine. Docker makes the setup portable — anyone can run the same container without installing nginx manually.

## What I Think Needs Upgrade

1. **IP changes** — If my IP address changes, the app is not accessible again. This has been solved using elastic Ip.
2. **Security** — Sharing my IP address is not safe. It exposes my machine directly.

## What Can Be Done?

1. Find a tool that maps an IP address to a domain name, so I use the domain name all the time.
2. Find a tool that keeps the app accessible even when my IP changes.

## CI/CD Pipeline — What It Actually Solves

My CI/CD should solve the problem of me manually deploying the app. Once I push to GitHub and the workflow runs, whatever changes I have made will be automatically deployed — instead of me building the Docker image and pushing again.

**What it does NOT solve:** The app still runs on my laptop. When my laptop dies, the app dies. CI/CD only automates the build process, not the hosting.

## Next Step (Hour 5)

- **Problem:** App only runs on my laptop, not available 24/7
- **Approach:** Rent a cloud VM that stays on all the time, deploy the container there
- **Disadvantages:** Cost (even when no one visits), need to monitor it, manual SSH for updates
- **Tool:** AWS EC2 (the VM), Docker Hub (image storage), GitHub Actions SSH step (auto-deploy)
